data.content:
This code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`**, which is good — but the manual `Thread` management pattern is the kind of code that often *pairs with* `Thread.Abort` at call sites. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`.

Here's the modern replacement using **`Parallel.ForEach`** with cooperative cancellation via `CancellationToken`:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items, CancellationToken ct = default)
    {
        Parallel.ForEach(items, new ParallelOptions { CancellationToken = ct }, item =>
        {
            Process(item, ct);
        });
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item, CancellationToken ct)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        // simulate work — use ct instead of Thread.Sleep
        Task.Delay(100, ct).Wait(ct);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

**Key migration points:**

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationToken.Cancel()` (cooperative) |
| `new Thread(() => …)` | `Parallel.ForEach` / `Task.Run` |
| `Thread.Sleep` | `Task.Delay(ms, ct)` for cancellable waits |
| `ThreadAbortException` | `OperationCanceledException` |

**Why this matters:** `Thread.Abort` was dangerous (corrupted state mid-execution). Cooperative cancellation via `CancellationToken` lets each method check at safe points and clean up properly. Audit any callers of `SimpleWorker` for `Thread.Abort` calls targeting these threads — those are the real migration hazards.
